WEBVTT

00:00:00.960 --> 00:00:05.920
Good afternoon, everyone. My name is Claire, and I'm so excited to be here at Posit.com this year.

00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:13.360
Slides disappeared in the back. On behalf of Coda, to tell you about our solution to navigating

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:20.320
complex real-world data using R. At Coda, we use technology analytics and oncology expertise to

00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:26.080
create clarity from real-world cancer data. However, like any other data user, we've had

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:32.000
a lot of challenges refining data for a given study analysis. To solve this, our team of data

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:38.400
scientists and statisticians have developed an R package. It's called rwnavigator, or real-world

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:45.599
navigator. Talking about rwnavigator, our package, which its sole purpose is to help users easily

00:00:45.599 --> 00:00:50.000
prepare real-world oncology data for use with gold standard survival analysis packages.

00:00:50.959 --> 00:00:56.720
Okay, to summarize the essence of rwnavigator, this package is a fast-forward button for creating

00:00:56.720 --> 00:01:02.080
sleek, clinically-informed, one-row-per-patient data tables to facilitate cancer outcomes research.

00:01:02.639 --> 00:01:08.320
Being able to speed up research studies that could result in important discoveries about

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:13.360
cancer treatment and care sounds pretty nice, right? Well, it wasn't exactly an easy path to

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:19.279
success, and even though the genesis of rwnavigator itself happened only about a year and a half ago,

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:25.360
the journey actually goes back years in COTA's history. For as long as we've collaborated on

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:29.919
research studies, we've been asked by our provider and life sciences partners about how we get from

00:01:29.919 --> 00:01:36.160
the complex cancer data that they see to the clear study results we present. Some common questions

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:41.680
include, why are there so many patients whose characteristics remain unknown? How do I pick

00:01:41.680 --> 00:01:47.120
a sensor date across all of these tables? What variables should I consider as an event for a

00:01:47.120 --> 00:01:51.839
given time-to-event endpoint? The good thing is, these are all questions that have already

00:01:51.839 --> 00:01:57.519
been fielded by our own research team over time. Using the knowledge of our medical experts and

00:01:57.519 --> 00:02:02.239
oncologists, we've created a unique clinically-informed perspective on the optimal use of

00:02:02.239 --> 00:02:08.639
our data. To make this perspective scalable across all our internal projects and also give external

00:02:08.639 --> 00:02:12.880
users access to the same knowledge, we took a step back to look at the bigger picture.

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:18.479
We quickly discovered common threads connecting many of our data preparation processes for

00:02:18.479 --> 00:02:23.360
time-to-event analysis. We're already leveraging variables across our data tables that were

00:02:23.360 --> 00:02:28.479
specific to our data model to answer key research questions. So why not build functionality that

00:02:28.479 --> 00:02:33.199
would not only help users replicate our research from beginning to end, but also simplify and

00:02:33.199 --> 00:02:40.320
standardize our own code? Thus, the idea for rwnavigator was born. So the overarching goal

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:44.880
of our package was to have well-tested, clearly-defined functions that could identify,

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:49.839
clean, and organize patient data across multiple tables in a one-row-per-patient fashion.

00:02:50.479 --> 00:02:54.800
Most data users we work with, along with our own team of analysts, including myself,

00:02:54.800 --> 00:02:59.520
are proficient users of R. So we wanted to create something that would not reinvent the wheel for

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:04.080
survival analysis, since there are existing packages that do that really well. Rather,

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:08.320
we wanted to add something that could be easily implemented into our workflow in order to

00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:14.080
elegantly produce these one-row-per-patient tables. This would accelerate the manipulation

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:17.679
of our data into something compatible with standard survival analysis.

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:25.039
There were other important considerations on top of these prerequisites. One was to include user

00:03:25.039 --> 00:03:31.279
autonomy in selecting data from specific tables, rather than all tables in the environment that

00:03:31.279 --> 00:03:36.800
included a given variable. For example, in calculating real-world overall survival for

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:41.919
a set of patients, if there was no date of death recorded for a given patient, they may have last

00:03:41.919 --> 00:03:46.960
been recorded to be alive anywhere from being contacted by their provider to going in for a

00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:52.240
lab assessment. However, a researcher may not consider lab result times a potential event

00:03:52.240 --> 00:03:57.119
indicator, and thus they could eliminate that particular data table from consideration for

00:03:57.119 --> 00:04:04.000
identifying the last time a patient was recorded as alive. Once we were able to identify and

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.399
calculate the event of interest, again here it's death, we had to consider an index date to

00:04:08.399 --> 00:04:13.360
calculate the amount of follow-up time to that event. So in oncology research, a good anchor

00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:19.040
point is the date of disease diagnosis or the initiation of a treatment regimen. However,

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:23.359
cancer patients may often receive more than one treatment cycle in their entire journey,

00:04:23.359 --> 00:04:27.200
and not all patients will receive the same number of treatment cycles for a given disease,

00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:32.399
resulting in multiple index states. I'm really sorry, what happened to one-row-per-patient?

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.880
Do I get to finish or do I have to go? Okay.

00:04:40.160 --> 00:04:41.679
Thank you, Claire. Thank you, Claire.

